text=Most people simply boil the tar outten them sprouts, but learned people know that steaming is better; this recipe, however, takes sprouts out of the ordinary veggie accompaniment and into a whole new territory.%0a%0a[[#ingredients]]%0a!!Ingredients%0a(:comment bulleted list of ingredients, with notes if necessary:)%0a* 2-3 cups Brussels sprouts, cut in half with yellowed leaves removed%0a* 1 large shallot, sliced and separated%0a* 2 slices bacon, cut into 1/2 inch pieces%0a* 1 tbsp olive oil%0a* sea salt%0a* freshly ground black pepper%0a%0a%0a[[#directions]]%0a!!Directions%0a(:comment ordered list of steps to follow:)%0a%0a# Heat oven to 350{$DegF}.%0a%0a# Combine ingredients in an oven safe casserole and mix well.%0a%0a# Cook 35-40 minutes, stirring 3-4 times, until Brussels sprouts are browned all around.%0a%0a# Serve hot, with an extra sprinkling of sea salt.%0a%0a(:comment         Other sections as desired, remove if false/ifend pairs  to use:)%0a%0a[[#variations]]%0a!!Variations%0a%0aUsing sesame oil instead of olive oil (using a lot less!) gives these a real tasty turn.%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a!!Comments%0a%0aThis dish goes great alongside DijonChicken. Instead of using a casserole dish, line a 9x13 inch baking pan with foil and spread the sprout mixture over about 2/3rds of the pan and bake at 350 for 20 minutes or so (enough time to get the chicken ready), then arrange the chicken in the other 1/3rd and lower the temp to 350 and bake an additional 30 minutes.%0a%0a(:if false:)%0aSummary:this dish takes the sprout beyond the basic boiling or steaming and into new territory%0aParent:(Recipes.)SideDishes%0aIncludeMe:[[Recipes.SideDishes]]%0aTags:brussels sprouts %0a(:tags-hide brussels sprouts :)%0aCategories:[[!SideDish]]%0aSource: [[http://sarahscucinabella.com/2007/11/16/roasted-brussels-sprouts-with-bacon-and-shallots-2/|sarahscucinabella.com]]%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a
